{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489824"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"750"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/750"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.08,0.45,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106663"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6045"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106663"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department and is admitted with a two-day history of right upper quadrant pain, nausea and vomiting. She has eaten very little over the previous 24 hours. She has a medical history of type II diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her medications include metformin, perindopril and simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she looks unwell. Her pulse rate is 108/min, blood pressure 110/65mmHg, temperature of 39.4\u00b0C and BMI 33kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There is loss of skin turgor and her abdomen is soft, apart from tenderness in the right subcostal region. A CT scan shows a thick-walled gallbladder with locules of gas within the wall. Intravenous fluids and antibiotics are started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is reviewed 12 hours later, when she has had 4L of intravenous fluid replacement and an antibiotic regimen of tazobactam and piperacillin. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 95/60mmHg, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. Her urine output since admission has been 560ml. She has become confused and her abdominal signs remain unchanged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current plan of management","Change the antibiotic regimen","Increase rate of intravenous fluid replacement","Percutaneous cholecystostomy","Semi-urgent laparoscopic cholecystectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has admitted to hospital with acute cholecystitis. In most such circumstances the patient would undergo \u003Cstrong\u003Echolecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E during that admission and ideally this should be done within two days of admission. Factors such as age of the patient and the presence of any co-morbidities will obviously influence any decision on the appropriateness of surgical intervention. In this case, the patient is obese and has two important co-morbidities, namely hypertension and type 2 diabetes. However, her main problem is her overall condition and she is now obviously septic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture, together with the CT findings of an emphysematous cholecystitis, suggest gangrenous cholecystitis. This is a well recognised, but uncommon complication of acute cholecystitis. As this patient has developed sepsis and is not responding to conservative treatment (fluids and antibiotics), continuing the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecurrent plan of management\u003C/strong\u003E will not make any significant difference, and a more active approach is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPart of the management plan for a patient with acute cholecystitis will be antibiotics if there is evidence of a secondary systemic bacterial infection. Typically, \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E,\u00a0\u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella\u003C/em\u003E, enterococci, and \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas\u003C/em\u003E are the cause behind a secondary bacterial infection. This patient has deteriorated since admission and is obviously septic. Her treatment so far has failed to improve her overall condition and \u003Cstrong\u003Echanging the antibiotic regimen\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing the rate of intravenous fluid replacement\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to make any significant difference and a more active intervention is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe source of the sepsis must be dealt with - this can be done most expediently by \u003Cstrong\u003Epercutaneous cholecystostomy\u003C/strong\u003E. In other circumstances a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E might be appropriate, but this patient is too ill for such a procedure at the moment. The relative contraindications of general anaesthesia should also be considered. This patient has risk factors associated with prolonged operative time and as conservative management has been unsuccessful, a lower risk procedure should be considered in preference to a laparoscopic cholecystectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute cholecystitis is usually treated by cholecystectomy during the initial admission.","Percutaneous cholecystostomy can be a temporising measure for patients unfit for surgical intervention."],"references":["Dhir T, Schiowitz R. Old man gallbladder syndrome: Gangrenous cholecystitis in the unsuspected patient population. Int J Surg Case Rep. 2015;11:46-49. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25917175/","Claesson B, Holmlund D, M\u00e4tzsch T. Biliary microflora in acute cholecystitis and the clinical implications. Acta Chir Scand. 1984;150(3):229-37. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6380177/","Warttig S, Ward S, Rogers G; Guideline Development Group. Diagnosis and management of gallstone disease: summary of NICE guidance. BMJ. 2014 Oct 30;349:g6241. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25360037/","Baron TH, Jorge I, Husnain A, et al. Comprehensive Review of the Management of Patients with Acute Cholecystitis Who Are Ineligible for Surgery. Ann Surg. 2025; April"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89142"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T15:26:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T15:26:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106663"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"item